      William Loughborough wrote:  >   > I get a very strong feeling that we are all tacitly assuming that the  > Web and all our Guidelines, etc. assume literacy on the part of a user?  > Of course this is the basis of Jonathan's criticisms and also the  > explanation of our emphasis on "text" as being fundamental.    > I don't think this is "wrong" but perhaps just unremarked.    I think there are other reasons (and I'm deriving these comments  from discussions with Eric Hansen):    1) All content must be available only to eyes, only to ears, and  only to fingertips. (Refer to my comments on grouping checkpoints  and the category of perception and the senses.)    [1] http://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/w3c-wai-gl/2000JulSep/0197.html    2) Given the state of current technologies (that are readily available,  not too expensive, and accurate enough), text is the best way to  ensure that information can reach all of those senses. Text is not  ideal for communicating all information (graphics and audio are often a   lot more effective than text, some users can't read visually displayed  text,  deaf non-readers seem to lose entirely in this model, etc.) However,  today's tools handle text characters as input much better than  images of text (OCR) or voice-to-text translation (although that seems  to be improving). How good is general visual-to-auditory translation?  Or auditory-to-visual?    Thus, I think the emphasis on text is not strictly bound to  assumptions of literacy but requirements to reach eyes, ears,  and fingertips.     - Ian    --   Ian Jacobs (jacobs@w3.org)   http://www.w3.org/People/Jacobs  Tel:                         +1 831 457-2842  Cell:                        +1 917 450-8783        

